== History == Although the hot spring river has long been known to flow through the area, the origin of Kawayu as a {{ill|therapeutic bathing site|ja|湯治場|12=draft|12=draft}} is uncertain. As for lodging, records indicate that a hot spring inn was established in {{ill|1886|ja|1886|12=draft|12=draft}} (Meiji 19), but it soon closed after becoming a gambling den for laborers working at Sulfur Mountain. Later, in {{ill|1904|ja|1904|12=draft|12=draft}} (Meiji 37), a hot spring inn built in Russian style was established, which is considered the origin of the current Kawayu Onsen.
Until the Taishō period, only that one inn operated modestly, but during the Shōwa period, with the opening of automobile roads, the {{ill|Kushiro Main Line|ja|釧網本線|12=draft|12=draft}} opened in {{ill|1930|ja|1930|12=draft|12=draft}} (Shōwa 5), and in {{ill|1934|ja|1934|12=draft|12=draft}} (Shōwa 9) the {{ill|Akan National Park|ja|阿寒国立公園|12=draft|12=draft}} was established, which spurred a rapid increase in therapeutic bathers.<ref>[http://www.iionsen.com/rekishi/donna.html What is Kawayu Onsen?] {{ill|Kawayu Onsen Tourism Hotel|ja|川湯観光ホテル|12=draft|12=draft}}</ref>
During the 【[Second World War]】, tourism demand cooled, and soon after the war in {{ill|1948|ja|1948|12=draft|12=draft}} (Shōwa 23), a major fire struck the area,<ref>[http://www.town.teshikaga.hokkaido.jp/teshikaga/gaiyou/gaiyou_data.html Timeline of the Town] {{ill|Teshikaga Town|ja|弟子屈町|12=draft|12=draft}}</ref> among other hardships. However, following the massive success of the film "{{ill|Your Name|ja|君の名は|12=draft|12=draft}}"—which featured the area around {{ill|Kussharo Lake|ja|屈斜路湖|12=draft|12=draft}} as a filming location—tourism surged once again, and the hot spring town rapidly developed.
Until the 1970s, winter road closures were common, but subsequent improvements in snow removal and road maintenance have established a system that attracts hot spring guests year-round. In its peak year, {{ill|1991|ja|1991|12=draft|12=draft}} (Heisei 3), 734,000 overnight guests visited.<ref name=":0">{{Cite news|title=Expecting Revival in Kawayu Onsen Town; "Bettei Nintō" Reopens on High-End Route / Budget Guest House Also Opens|date=2021-04-19|newspaper={{ill|Hokkaido Shimbun|ja|北海道新聞|12=draft|12=draft}}|url=https://www.hokkaido-np.co.jp/article/534926|accessdate=2021-04-20|archiveurl=https://archive.ph/g67kj|archivedate=2021-04-20}}</ref>
However, thereafter the number of guests continued to decline. The self-restraint mood following the {{ill|Great East Japan Earthquake|ja|東日本大震災|12=draft|12=draft}} in {{ill|2011|ja|2011|12=draft|12=draft}} (Heisei 23), as well as the effects of the {{ill|Hokkaido Eastern Iburi Earthquake|ja|北海道胆振東部地震|12=draft|12=draft}} in {{ill|2018|ja|2018|12=draft|12=draft}} (Heisei 30), also had significant impacts.<ref name=":1">{{Cite web|url=https://hotelbank.jp/kawayu-suikazura/|title=Kawayu Hotel Plaza Acquires Closed Hotels, Aiming to Reopen in January 2021|accessdate=2021-04-20|publisher={{ill|HotelBank|ja|ホテルバンク|12=draft|12=draft}}|archivedate=2021-04-19|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20210419154425/https://hotelbank.jp/kawayu-suikazura/}}</ref> As of {{ill|2020|ja|2020|12=draft|12=draft}} (Reiwa 2), due to ongoing poor business conditions, about 10 hotels and ryokan remain closed, with some having become abandoned ruins that pose a local landscape issue.<ref name=":1" /> Additionally, the impact of the {{ill|COVID-19 pandemic|ja|新型コロナウイルス感染拡大|12=draft|12=draft}} resulted in only 91,000 overnight guests in the 2020 fiscal year (Reiwa 2).
Regarding the origin of the name "Kawayu," when translating the Ainu term "セセキペツ" (meaning "hot river"), since a hot spring known as {{ill|Yunokawa Onsen|ja|湯の川温泉|12=draft|12=draft}} (an Ainu translation of "ユベツ" meaning "hot water river") already existed in the vicinity of {{ill|Hakodate|ja|函館|12=draft|12=draft}}, the order was reversed to form "Kawayu." == Access == * Rail: About 10 minutes by {{ill|Akan Bus|ja|阿寒バス|12=draft|12=draft}} from {{ill|Kawayu Onsen Station|ja|川湯温泉駅|12=draft|12=draft}} on the {{ill|Kushiro Main Line|ja|釧網本線|12=draft|12=draft}}. * By Private Car: Via the {{ill|Dōtō Expressway|ja|道東自動車道|12=draft|12=draft}} from the {{ill|Ashiyori Interchange|ja|足寄インターチェンジ|12=draft|12=draft}}, along {{ill|National Route 241|ja|国道241号|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|National Route 391|ja|国道391号|12=draft|12=draft}}. == References == {{Footnote Help}} {{Reflist}}
