Until the 1970s, winter road closures were common, but subsequent improvements in snow removal and road maintenance have established a system that attracts hot spring guests year-round. In its peak year, {{ill|1991|ja|1991|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1991|qq=}} (Heisei 3), 734,000 overnight guests visited.<ref name=":0">{{Cite news|title=Expecting Revival in Kawayu Onsen Town; "Bettei Nintō" Reopens on High-End Route / Budget Guest House Also Opens|date=2021-04-19|newspaper={{ill|Hokkaido Shimbun|ja|北海道新聞|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hokkaido Shimbun|qq=}}|url=https://www.hokkaido-np.co.jp/article/534926|accessdate=2021-04-20|archiveurl=https://archive.ph/g67kj|archivedate=2021-04-20}}</ref>
However, thereafter the number of guests continued to decline. The self-restraint mood following the {{ill|Great East Japan Earthquake|ja|東日本大震災|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Great East Japan Earthquake|qq=}} in {{ill|2011|ja|2011|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/2011|qq=}} (Heisei 23), as well as the effects of the {{ill|Hokkaido Eastern Iburi Earthquake|ja|北海道胆振東部地震|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hokkaido Eastern Iburi Earthquake|qq=}} in {{ill|2018|ja|2018|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/2018|qq=}} (Heisei 30), also had significant impacts.<ref name=":1">{{Cite web|url=https://hotelbank.jp/kawayu-suikazura/|title=Kawayu Hotel Plaza Acquires Closed Hotels, Aiming to Reopen in January 2021|accessdate=2021-04-20|publisher={{ill|HotelBank|ja|ホテルバンク|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/HotelBank|qq=}}|archivedate=2021-04-19|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20210419154425/https://hotelbank.jp/kawayu-suikazura/}}</ref> As of {{ill|2020|ja|2020|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/2020|qq=}} (Reiwa 2), due to ongoing poor business conditions, about 10 hotels and ryokan remain closed, with some having become abandoned ruins that pose a local landscape issue.<ref name=":1" /> Additionally, the impact of the {{ill|COVID-19 pandemic|ja|新型コロナウイルス感染拡大|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/COVID-19 pandemic|qq=}} resulted in only 91,000 overnight guests in the 2020 fiscal year (Reiwa 2).
Regarding the origin of the name "Kawayu," when translating the Ainu term "セセキペツ" (meaning "hot river"), since a hot spring known as {{ill|Yunokawa Onsen|ja|湯の川温泉|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yunokawa Onsen|qq=}} (an Ainu translation of "ユベツ" meaning "hot water river") already existed in the vicinity of {{ill|Hakodate|ja|函館|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hakodate|qq=}}, the order was reversed to form "Kawayu." == Access == * Rail: About 10 minutes by {{ill|Akan Bus|ja|阿寒バス|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Akan Bus|qq=}} from {{ill|Kawayu Onsen Station|ja|川湯温泉駅|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kawayu Onsen Station|qq=}} on the {{ill|Kushiro Main Line|ja|釧網本線|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kushiro Main Line|qq=}}. * By Private Car: Via the {{ill|Dōtō Expressway|ja|道東自動車道|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Dōtō Expressway|qq=}} from the {{ill|Ashiyori Interchange|ja|足寄インターチェンジ|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ashiyori Interchange|qq=}}, along {{ill|National Route 241|ja|国道241号|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/National Route 241|qq=}} and {{ill|National Route 391|ja|国道391号|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/National Route 391|qq=}}. == References ==
